Reviews of Swedish Asylum Age Assessment
Recent results of tests for asylum seekers in Sweden, which have undergone a new method of medical assessment of their age, show that more than 80% of the people tested are over 18 years old, but not everyone believes in the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish authority for forensic medicine (Rätsmedicinalverkaet) has started carrying out the tests last year.
They are supposed to make the assessment of age more accurate during the asylum procedure, after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migration Trading) was criticised for errors in assessing the correct age of some refugees who were minors.
To date, Migration Verket has sent out 6,880 testing cases, and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests from mid-March to July 31, 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) were judged to be 18 or older, while in another 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency judged that the person was "possibly 18 years or older".
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person was' possibly under 18 years old '.
The tests are carried out only in cases where the age of the person is questioned.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results have been consistent over the past few months.
"We see no big difference in statistics of recent months, the numbers are quite constant," he said to the magazine The Local.
The high percentage of cases in which the person was judged to be over 18 years does not necessarily mean that the asylum seeker lied over his or her age.
In May, the Agency published the results of 581 tests and said that there were 442 cases proposing 'that the person investigated be 18 years or older'.
When the Svenska Dagbladet newspaper examined the 581 published results, it found that in 243 of these cases the person had frankly said that she was 18 years old this year.
The method of medical age assessment, in which x-rays of wisdom teeth and MRT shots of knee joints are taken, which are then analyzed by dentists and radiologists, has also been criticised in some areas.
A skeptic is the endocrinologist Claude Marcus of the Carolinska Institute, whose work includes assessing the biological maturity of humans to see whether they passed through puberty sooner or later than usual.
"I had reason to think about it and I do not think that the type of measurement should be used.
Assessing biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we cannot say it safely, we should not act as if we could, "he said to the Metro newspaper.
Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, however, defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, you can say that the risk of judging a child incorrectly as an adult is low.
The biggest risk is when the person is under 18, in this case it is about 10%. '
