In its quarterly inflation report, the Bank reduced its growth forecasts for 2017 to 1.7% and for 2018 to 1.6%, warning that fiscal pressure would continue, with inflation expected to rise to just under 3% in the autumn.
But it signaled that interest-rate hikes would be needed in the coming years to rein in the inflation fueled by Brexit, and it said that borrowing costs might have to rise more than expected in financial markets.
Members also voted to withdraw part of the mammoth stimulus package issued a year ago after Brexit.
It will require time for the financing plan to provide cheaper funding for banks from next February, although it has been said that it is now expected to provide GBP 15 billion more under this system - GBP 115 billion.
Minutes after deciding on the interest rate, the Bank said: "In the MPC ’ s central forecast, GDP remains weak in the short term, as pressure on real household incomes continues to burden consumption."
At interest rates, she repeated that "some monetary tightening" would be needed to cool inflation and a "slightly larger" extent than markets expect.
The markets are currently forecasting the first increase in the third quarter of next year and another in 2020.
However, the Bank stressed that increases would be 'gradual' and 'limited'.
The Bank ’ s downward revised growth forecasts for this year and next year compare to the 1.9% and 1.7% projected in May.
It has maintained its growth forecast to 1.8% in 2018.
The pound fell against the dollar and the euro after this news.
The pound fell by 0.5% to $1.31 and fell by 0.4% to €1.11.
