National Health Service (NHS), a controversial HIV drug, is supposed to prescribe 10,000 people.
Patients will have access to "transformative" HIV prevention treatment from September, following a fight in front of the High Court against funding of the drug in the NHS.
NHS England announced that a pre-sexual preexposure prophylaxis (PrEP), which can reduce the risk of infection in high-risk patients by around 86%, is now delivered by the health service through a first three-year study for an estimated 10,000 people.
He agreed to finance the trial after last year's appeal court confirmed a Supreme Court ruling that the NHS had the power to pay for the PrEP despite claiming that local authorities should finance it.
The move announced on Thursday was welcomed by NHS England chief Simon Stevens as "important new intervention," while the National AIDS Trust (NAT) called it a "decisive moment."
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool, and Sheffield will be among the first to allow people to register, and more clinics will follow in October, before it will be introduced throughout England in April 2018.
Preexposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a consequence of HIV preparations taken before sex in order to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in cases of infection.
Taking PrEP before sexual intercourse means that there are just enough drugs in a person ’ s body to prevent HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken every day or even two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transsexuals, and people with HIV positive partners who have not been successfully treated.
In clinics, suitable participants are identified who agree to the study, including men, women, transgender, and individuals who have a partner whose HIV status is not known to be controlled by antiretroviral treatment.
People who live in England and are registered with a family doctor can also register for participation in their local participating sex clinic.
The program will be £10 million and NHS England signed a contract to supply the drugs this week after an international competitive procurement.
The study is intended to assess the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence, as it is targeted, recorded, and implemented on a large scale.
Stevens said: "This major new intervention should complement and overtake the far-reaching and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in more than three decades of progress in tackling one of humanity's greatest health challenges. "
Deborah Gold, Chief Executive at NAT (National AIDS Trust), said: "This is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, when targeted at people in need and in danger, offers the opportunity to change the English HIV epidemic.
From September onwards, people with high HIV risks will have access to this NHS-funded attempt in England to develop a new instrument that is genuinely individually controlled and not subject to negotiation with a partner, which will improve many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this announcement. '
Ian Green, Chairman of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: "The priority must now be that the study is carried out quickly throughout the country and that no one with a risk of HIV is left behind.
Now that PrEP testing has been obtained, we are on the way to protecting more than 10,000 people infected with HIV. '
Sharon Hodgson, the shadow health minister, said: "The beginning of the PrEP process is welcome and overdue after months of delays and delays by the government.
The evidence shows how transformative this drug can be part of our approach to HIV prevention and can stop transmission of this life-changing infection.
This attempt brings us a step closer to understanding the advantages of PrEP.
It is now important that this study be carried out as quickly as possible throughout the country in order to protect people who are infected with HIV and that it will help bring us a step closer to ending the spread of HIV in society '.
Living the Great Life: mezzanine and clever designer tricks have transformed this small Earls Court apartment into a generous home.
Joanne Leigh, a former banker with a passion for real estate, reduced from a large house in Knightsbridge to an Earls Court apartment in 2014.
It is located on the first floor of an elegant Queen Anne Terrace - and it is proof of the new design that Joanne did not pack and sell her bags.
"Before that I lived with my Ex in Knightsbridge in a much larger room," says Joanne.
"I was looking for something comparable to my price.
I was shown this apartment in Earls Court and she had the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with them and made an offer on that day. '
Since the first visit, the 1.000 square foot apartment has been completely overtaken.
Originally a one-room property with a nested layout - you had to go through the kitchen to get into the bedroom - Joanne wanted to add storage space and a mezzanine to make the most of the spacious ceiling.
"I wanted high ceilings, large windows, lots of light.
That was my request, "she says.
To this end, she commissioned the architectural and design studio Duck & Shed of Erfan Azadi of Notting Hill to use the 12,5 foot high ceilings and create a home that was not only a development, but also a place to live Joanne.
The ceiling was not large enough to place two rooms on top of each other, so the architectural challenge was to create a mezzanine in which one could stand.
Erfan had to think creatively to solve the problem.
"The steel mill is quite complicated," he explains.
"We had to arrange the rooms in such a way that they were stacked on top of each other, without having to bend.
It was not just a question of building a simple platform, but of putting the steel in such a way that it had the right height for the function above or below. '
This arrangement allowed Erfan to place two rooms on top of each other - with much additional drama.
For the mezzanine, the classic Retrouvius copper light window looks down over the glamorous living area.
Played gold furniture, silver accents and vintage Serge Mouille lighting set the tone for the program.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding theatre, space and light.
A short corridor is mirrored at both ends to allow it to work longer.
In the kitchen, mirroring feels like a window into another room.
At the entrance, mirrored units offer space for all Joanne cutlery and glasses.
By perceiving a more glamorous space, the beauty of the living room can close the kitchen if it is not used.
Connectable kitchens are nothing new.
What is special about this is that it is a garage door.
"A bit of engineering came in," explains Erfan of the steel reinforced veneered MDF door.
'It is counterweight, so when you push the door up, it glides very easily. '
Thanks to the clever use of space and storage space, Joanne was able to gain an additional 16 m ², an additional bedroom and an improved layout.
"At the end of the day you will sell the base area - or how your property is estimated," says Erfan.
'In a rudimentary form, a real estate agent will enter and carry out a calculation based on land size '.
Here they have managed to enlarge the floor area and at the same time to use high-quality materials that give the room its luxurious advantage.
"The materials are the things you touch and which therefore help to create an emotional bond in a home," says Erfan.
"You don't fall in love with the electrical sockets in the walls.
These are important, but they do not play with your heart. '
It shows that an apartment can be transformed into something quite amazing by its good design and increased square meters of something standard.
Indeed, like Joanne, you could decide not to leave it.
Brothers Fight for a $500 million Real Estate Imperium
Two brothers, four decades after their Italian family founded the dynasty, are in a dispute over one of Victorias ’ largest real-estate empires worth more than $500 million.
Former Director of the 'Carlton Football Club' and developer Colin De Lutis lives in a villa in Toorak, just three doors away from his younger brother Paul, who brought him to the Supreme Court to clarify how their property and assets are to be shared.
Paul wanted to leave the family business since 2014, but a sharp dispute about separation is taking place in the Supreme Court.
Together with her mother Anna, the brothers own 38 properties worth more than half a billion dollars, accumulated since the family bought a store in Smith Street, Collingwood, in 1973.
There, the Westco Jeans family founded and grew into a chain of 160 retail stores.
It was sold for USD 85 million in 1999.
This money has been invested in real estate, and De Lutis ’ portfolio now includes city centre offices, Brunswick and Sorrento development areas, Gold Coast and Mt Buller apartments, and suburban shopping centres.
According to an agreement with her deceased father, Colin - described by Paul as "the main operator and the dominant personality" in the De Lutis family - owns about two-thirds of the company's assets and Paul about a third.
A lawsuit says that this means that Colin owns $316 million worth of property and $176 million worth of Paul.
The distribution of real estate and cash has proved to be a problem for Paul.
"The divisions proposed by Colin left him with what I thought were the best objects," he wrote in a first affidavit in 2015.
Last Friday, the first Supreme Court hearing took place after several failed conciliations.
The brothers are now also fighting for control of the existing business, which Colin, as Paul claims, has ruled out.
Colin argues that this is not true, but accuses Paul of administering some possessions incompetently.
In an early affidavit submitted by Colin, he says he hopes to settle the dispute.
"My Italian heritage stipulates that the family is the most important priority," he wrote.
Costs rise in this case, with hundreds of pages of affidavits, e-mails and reports from companies, including Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Cramer, and leading lawyers, including Allan Myers, QC, and law firms held by both sides.
Mrs. De Lutis and her late husband Luigi were Italian immigrants who operated dairy bars and delicatessen shops from the late 1950s and bought a shop in Brunswick in the early 1970s.
They used the security to buy the Collingwood property, where Colin opened the family ’ s first jeans store.
Colin says he started Westco there when he was "high school in my last years, when Paul was still a small child (about 10 years old)."
Anna De Lutis says that she and Luigi, who died in 2012, hoped to pass on their property gracefully to their sons.
"Luigi often said to me that he never wanted the brothers to land in court," she wrote.
Two other brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of the De Lutis group, with Colin claiming that Mark was paid $10 million and Luke $26 million when leaving the company.
Both Lukas and Mark, Paul says, have "become bitter about the conditions of their financial separation".
Colin has been very reluctant even though he was a former AFL board member and Eddie McGuire ’ s best friend of the television star after a 2015 biography.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul De Lutis and their lawyers.
Only Colin answered by SMS to say "I really can't say much", because the case is in the courts.
"It is very, very sad that my brother Paul has decided to sue me and to take our family name through the courts," he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote to the court that he had tried to meet his brother ’ s demands.
"Our father did not want Paul and I to end up in our current dispute," he said, adding that he "still hope for a solution".
On Friday, that hope seemed to be over.
"Our matter will be resolved by the courts in the near future," Colin wrote.
Trump ’ s new chief of staff plans to limit the president ’ s media abstinence.
Others tried and failed.
Perhaps John F. Kelly can actually do so.
If so, he will be the first.
Politico reports that the new White House Chief of Staff is planning to restrict the flow of information to President Trump, including news media reports, in the hope of keeping the boss on a more consistent course.
Here is a piece of reporter Josh Dawsey:
"When John F. Kelly, the new White House Chief of Staff, met senior officials on his first day of work, he posed a major problem in President Donald Trump ’ s White House, which he wanted to repair: bad information falling into the hands of the president.
Kelly told staff that information about him should flow - whether on paper or in briefings - because the president would make better decisions if he received good information. '
Kelly ’ s diagnosis makes sense, but others have tried to tame Trump by monitoring his media diet.
President Trump ’ s relationship with television goes back decades – and now that he is in the White House, his television advertising is still strong.
"If candidate Trump was annoyed about unfair reporting, it was productive to show him that he received fair coverage from persuasive posts," said former campaign adviser Sam Nunberg to Politico in February.
Politicos Tara Palmeri wrote at the time that "the key to keeping Trump's Twitter habit under control, according to six former campaign officials, is to ensure that his personal media consumption includes a constant praise."
Okay.
But the idea that Trump ’ s Twitter habit has ever been “under control ” is ridiculous.
Perhaps these campaign officials know something we others don ’ t know – that Trump ’ s tweets would have contained even more fuel without their interventions.
We will probably never hear about the tweets that Trump has not sent.
If his staff have managed to keep him out of trouble several times, then their efforts have been worthwhile.
But no one has consistently prevented Trump from inciting controversy.
Part of the problem is that, in a White House composed of competing parties, people keep trying to advance their own agenda by presenting Trump with material that might promote their views on the world.
Politico - dealing entirely with this story - reported in May on the consultants' preference to provide the president with dubious information for strategic reasons.
This was an example described by Reporter Shane Goldmacher:
"Current and former Trump officials say that Trump can respond like a volcano to negative press cuts, especially those with damaging leaks, and that he is obsessed with finding out where they come from.
That is exactly what happened at the end of February, when someone maliciously gave the president a printed copy of an article by GotNews.com, the Web site of Internet provocateur Charles C. Johnson, who accused deputy chief Katie Walsh of being "the source behind a pile of leaks" in the White House.
Although Johnson was permanently banned from Twitter for harassment, or offered no concrete evidence, or that in the past he had made false accusations and revoked them.
Trump read the article and began to ask staff about Walsh. "
Goldmacher added that then-Chief of Staff, Reince Priebus, and White House Secretary General Rob Porter, "tried to implement a system to manage and document the paperwork Trump receives."
How did that work?
Kelly tries to do the same three months later.
Perhaps he will prove to be a more effective manager than a priest, but Trump is still his impulsive self, and his advisers are still seeking influence.
These immutable factors make Kelly ’ s mission very difficult.
