From Birkenhof Goes Waldhotel Luise
The Waldhotel Luise will become the former Hotel Birkenhof.
The house at the gates of Freudenstadt is currently being renovated and is due to be reopened on 1 March next year.
This is good news for the city.
With the closure of Hotel Birkenhof by the then Ambiente Betriebsgesellschaft mbH on 13 April 2014, around 30 000 overnight stays per year were lost at the time and revenue from the visitor tax was also lost.
In the fall of 2014, with dramatically rising numbers of refugees entering the district, the hotel building was offered to the Board of Councillors as a collective accommodation, causing controversial debate.
The city prevented the accommodation of asylum seekers by establishing a building plan to secure the area as a hotel location.
The decision was not uncontroversial at the time in the municipal council.
But above all the joys of Lord Mayor Julian Osswald defended the hotel location and talked about serious guests at the hotel back then.
He should be right.
The Luisenhotels Group with its managing director Birgit Scherer, based in Bad Bergzabern, acquired the former Hotel Birkenhof at a voluntary auction in Berlin and wants to make it again a house of the three-star plus category under the name Waldhotel Luise.
The group has four houses with the Freudenstadt object.
Two of them in Bad Bergzabern and one in Bad Herrenalb.
They are called Hotel Luise, Luisenpark, Parkhotel Luise and now Waldhotel Luise.
