Russia affair: United States Special Counsel Creates Grand Jury
In the Russia affair of US President Donald Trump, Special Counsel Robert Mueller is reported to have appointed a grand jury.
The panel has started work in recent weeks, wrote the Wall Street Journal, citing people familiar with the matter.
The newspaper rated the move as a sign that Mueller expanded and intensified his investigation.
The CNN reported that there are already initial subpoenas from the panel in connection with a meeting between Trump ’ s eldest son and a Russian lawyer.
US intelligence agencies have long accused the Kremlin of deliberately interfering in the 2016 presidential election campaign.
Mueller investigates whether there were deals between Trump ’ s campaign and Moscow.
The investigation will focus on several men who campaigned as Republican advisers.
Mueller reportedly also looked more and more at Trump ’ s private and business environment.
The Washington Post wrote a few weeks ago that the special prosecutor, Trump, had personally put the spotlight on the charges of whether the president might have obstructed justice in the course of the affair.
The main task of Grand Jurys is to examine the evidence in possible criminal cases and decide whether to prosecute them.
Grand Jurys are therefore also called indictments.
In most cases, they are switched on when there are major and controversial cases.
The procedure always takes place behind closed doors.
The board can also be activated by the Public Prosecutor to invite people to interrogate under oath.
According to CNN, subpoenas have already been issued that revolve around the encounter between Donald Trump Jr. and a Russian lawyer.
People involved in the meeting were asked to make a statement, as the report said.
They should also provide documents.
In addition to Trump Jr., Trump ’ s advisers and son-in-law, Jared Kushner, and his then campaign leader, Paul Manafort, were also on the conversation.
Legal experts said on Thursday evening on US television that the investiture showed that Mueller did not let himself be intimidated in his work and that he wanted to act quickly if necessary.
However, it should not necessarily mean that the Grand Jury will be turned on at the end to decide whether to bring charges.
Nevertheless, the establishment of the body is the start of a new phase in the investigation and a new cause for concern for President Trump.
In the midst of the new revelations, the President used a speech in West Virginia on Thursday evening to portray the Russia affair as a campaign of his political opponents.
"Russia's history is a total invention," Trump said.
The issue gives democrats a chance to 'feel good because they have nothing else they can talk about'.
His special adviser, Ty Cobb, stated in an opinion that he knew nothing about the appointment of a Grand Jury.
But they usually work in secret, he emphasized.
The White House is in favour of any measures that accelerated the work of the Special Investigator in a 'fair' way.
Former FBI chief James Comey has said three times that the president is not being investigated.
There is no reason to believe that this has changed, the statement continued.
But Mueller had only been deployed after Trump fired Comey.
For this plot, charges against Trump had been raised that he wanted to obstruct the judiciary.
Comey told a Senate committee in June that Trump asked him to stop investigating then-national security adviser Michael Flynn.
The President is under great pressure because of the investigation.
According to the US media, the White House collected material against the Special Investigator and his staff.
This triggered speculation about whether Trump would release Mueller.
Unlike an independent congressional special investigator, such as the Watergate affair of late President Richard Nixon, Mueller has a position in which he could theoretically be fired by the Ministry of Justice at the President ’ s insistence.
But several senators from both parties want to prevent such a move.
On Thursday, two groups of Republican and Democratic senators presented draft legislation that would make it difficult for the Special Investigator to be dismissed.
