What happened in the following three years with Ferrell and Ferguson is the theme of a new documentary film, "Whose Streets?", in cinemas from the 11th century onwards.
It is a history of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and of the resilience that exists from the point of view of the people who live in the community and who have filled the streets to demand answers.
When Ferrell went to Ferguson with her daughter wearing a floral dress and a fitting crown, they talked about the black experience and the black state several times before this morning.
"You remember how I taught you when black people must fight for what they believe?" she remembered what she said.
"We are now going to Ferguson because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and that was not right.
I could not take them with me, "Ferrell said later.
"What happened today is a highlight of what happened in the past.
She must know it and see it and be raised in it.
It must be well developed, not only activism and organization, but also the various layers of black experience and the black constitution, and what we must do to become free to liberate ourselves.
Although I have the good fortune to give her an experience in which she personally does not experience blatant racism, she is no different from the next black female child.
I have the feeling that I am doing her a disservice by keeping her away from it. '
The first station, when it arrived in Ferguson, was on South Florissant Road, a site opposite the police force, which became a campus area when the activists were waiting for the possible non-prosecution of Officer Darren Wilson.
There Ferrell and her daughter joined a local business owner who had lunch.
They prepared bags and helped to pass them on to demonstrators.
A new type of activism for Ferrell slowly began to take shape.
"My activism has changed completely after August 9," she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri St Louis was President of the Minority Student Nurses Association and focused on food justice and health inequalities in black communities.
"I had no experience in organizing.
Everything has come. '
Weeks later, Ferrell met during an evening demonstration Sabaah Folayan, one of the film ’ s co-directors.
Folayan said that she and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar only wanted to "document" what happened.
Ferrell asked: 'Do you want to document or try to find a story you can exploit?'
This skepticism was fueled by countless cases of people, often whites, in a community that benefited from their pain and resilience.
As Folayan said in a recent interview: 'We heard that people born and raised in Ferguson did not centre their voices and we wanted to do it differently'.
Folayan had already worked with Damon Davis, a co-director at the time, an artist known for his activism around death row inmates.
His commitment brought Ferrell closer to the project, and together with six other locals the team of "Whose Streets?" followed in the years after Brown's shooting.
"This documentary is not someone who speaks for us or speaks to us.
'That was the main thing for me as these people are portrayed, because that is how I will be portrayed. '
The goal was not to focus on Ferrell's experience - to show that the movement "is not a Messias leader, but a community that comes together," said Folayan - she proved to be the most open participant in the film.
As a result, documents from "Whose Streets?" show surprisingly personal aspects of Ferrell ’ s life as she falls in love and marry her wife.
"I felt naked," Ferrell said and laughed when she first saw the finished product.
'But I understand that there must be some vulnerability in this work and in the humanisation of black people. '
In addition, Ferrell ’ s story repeats the role of black gay women in the broader Black-Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement, who after the killing of the black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 marked the film "BlacklivesMatter" in social media, identify themselves as gay.
"Black, gay women in management positions have carried the whole movement," Ferrell said, "and therefore we are constantly fighting on various fronts.
Black, gay women must bear the brunt of everything. '
Folayan agreed to note that "the movement is really maintained by black women and many black women".
However, she insists that "this is not an affirmative type of action", where Ferrell was chosen as the heart of the film because of her identity.
"She was the person who stirred up this energy," she said.
"It is no coincidence, although she was at the forefront, because in a life on these crossings as a black, gay woman is so much at stake.
You can feel their energy through the screen. '
Meanwhile, news cameras in Ferguson have long since disappeared, but racial links between the community and the police remain.
Ferrell is suspended for 2 ½ years because of the blocking of a highway during a demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the area she calls her home: "A Chaos".
However, she clings to singing and feels committed to this memory since she took to the streets in Ferguson three years ago.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
